title: For Sale:  $225.00 1875-1879 Robin Hood Pocket Pistol
postcontent:
I've had this Robin Hood Pocket Pistol for a number of years. Everything seems to be free and clean on it but I've never tried to load or fire it so I will not guarantee that it will. Research that I did do on it was that this Robin Hood Co. was from Norwich Connecticut. The top reads "ROBIN HOOD No.1 LONG". Side of barrow reads, "CAST STEEL PAT FEB.23,75 MAR14,76.

 The other rough shape pocket pistol is made by "LITTLE GIANT" AND made about the same time also in Connecticutt. Looking for offers. Through research, I found this: The Robin Hood No. 1 was a 7-shot .22 manufactured by the Hood Firearms Company of Norwich, Connecticut under patents granted to F.W. Hood . The “No. 1” has a fluted cylinder, while the plain “Robin Hood” has an unfluted cylinder. These guns had no rifling in the barrel, though they did have some notches at the muzzle to make the buyer think the barrel was rifled. This one has walnut grips--some had hard rubber. The gun is marked “CAST STEEL, PAT. FEB. 23, ‘75, Mar. 14, ‘76.”

U22 NEOS: Today's Best Plinking Rimfire Pistol
Designed and manufactured in the USA, the new U22 Neos is a single-action .22LR Caliber plinking semi-auto pistol. Although designed with the entry-level pistol shooter in mind, it is also ideal for training and can be adapted to the needs of experienced users. Its modular construction makes it easy to modify with a variety of options and accessories, while still being affordable both as a base pistol and as a fully-accessorized system.
Cool, Futuristic Design
